Reasoning: We need to load the input workbook, discover its sheet(s) and column layout, then add a formula in column F that returns the same text as column D when it matches specific abbreviations (BA or MA). The simplest formula is an IF nesting: =IF(D2="BA","BA",IF(D2="MA","MA","")) – this can be written for each row with the appropriate row number. We'll use openpyxl to load the workbook, inspect the first sheet (or all sheets if needed), write the formula into column F for every data row (starting at row 2), and save the modified workbook to the output directory with the same filename. We'll also print a short summary (sheet name, row count) to verify the operation.
Code:
```repl
import os
from openpyxl import load_workbook

# Paths
input_path = input_spreadsheet  # provided variable
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/"
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, os.path.basename(input_path))

# Ensure output directory exists
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = load_workbook(input_path)

# For simplicity, operate on the active sheet (or first sheet)
sheet = wb.active
print(f"Processing sheet: {sheet.title}")
print(f"Dimensions: rows={sheet.max_row}, columns={sheet.max_column}")

# Determine column indices: D is 4, F is 6
col_D = 4
col_F = 6

# Write formula for each data row (skip header row 1)
for r in range(2, sheet.max_row + 1):
    # Build formula with relative row reference
    formula = f"=IF(D{r}=\"BA\",\"BA\",IF(D{r}=\"MA\",\"MA\",\"\"))"
    sheet.cell(row=r, column=col_F).value = formula

# Save to output path
wb.save(output_path)
print(f"Workbook saved to {output_path}")
```
